\begin{abstract}
We define a normed/metric ultraproduct of normed topological groups and show that there is a sequence of finite normed groups whose metric ultraproduct contains isometrically as a subgroup every separable normed topological group.
\end{abstract}
\keywords{normed groups, left-invariant metric, metric ultraproducts}
\subjclass[2010]{22A05,20F65,03C20}
\maketitle
\section*{Introduction}
The motivation for this paper comes from the question of Mycielski in \cite{My} (asked for example also by Shkarin in \cite{Sk}) whether there exists a separable normed topological group (equivalently a separable topological group with left-invariant metric) which contains isometrically as a subgroup every separable normed topological group. One can see it as a geometric version of the question posed already in the Scottish book (\cite{SB}) whether there exists a universal second-countable topological group. That was answered positively by Uspenskij in \cite{Us1} and several other examples of universal second-countable topological groups have been found since then (see e.g. \cite{Us2}, \cite{BY}). We do not have an answer to this question, however we prove a result in this direction connecting it with the area of group embeddings into metric ultraproducts of groups. Although metric ultraproducts of groups are usually considered only for groups equipped with bi-invariant metrics, or equivalently with norms 
which are invariant on conjugacy classes, we shall define a metric ultraproduct of general normed topological groups and prove the following result.
\begin{thm}\label{main}
There exists a countable sequence of finite normed groups such that their metric ultraproduct contains isometrically as a subgroup every separable normed topological group.
\end{thm}
\section{Definitions and preliminaries}
\subsection{Norms and metrics on groups}
Let $G$ be a group. A \emph{norm} (or sometimes \emph{value} or, mainly in geometric group theory, a \emph{length function}) on $G$ is a function $\lambda:G\rightarrow {\mathbb{R}}_0^+$ with the following properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item $\lambda(x)=\lambda(x^{-1})$ for every $x\in G$,
\item $\lambda(x\cdot y)\leq \lambda(x)+\lambda(y)$ for every $x,y\in G$,
\item $\lambda(x)=0$ iff $x=1_G$.
\end{itemize}
$\lambda$ satisfying all except the last condition is called a \emph{seminorm}. Note that the property $\lambda(1)=0$ is satisfied automatically.

A (semi)norm $\lambda$ on $G$ satisfying $\lambda(g^{-1}\cdot h\cdot g)=\lambda(h)$ for every $g,h\in G$ is called \emph{conjugacy-invariant}.\\

Recall that a (pseudo)metric $d$ on the group $G$ is \emph{left-invariant} if $d(g\cdot x,g\cdot y)=d(x,y)$ for every $g,x,y\in G$. Right-invariance and bi-invariance are defined analogously.

There is a one-to-one correspondence between norms and left-invariant metrics (and analogously between seminorms and left-invariant pseudometrics). Indeed, given a left-invariant metric $d$, the formula $\lambda_d(x):=d(x,1_G)$ gives a norm on $G$, and conversely, given a norm $\lambda$ on $G$, the formula $d_\lambda(x,y):=\lambda(x^{-1}\cdot y)$ gives a left-invariant metric. 

Moreover, if the metric $d$ was bi-invariant, the the formula above gives a conjugacy-invariant norm. Conversely, if the norm $\lambda$ was conjugacy-invariant, then the formula above gives a bi-invariant metric.

It turns out it is more convenient for us to work with norms rather than metrics, so we will do so in the sequel.\\

It follows that (semi)norms on groups define a topology there. However, the topology on a group $G$ determined by some (semi)norm $\lambda$ on $G$ does not in general make it a topological group; i.e. the group operations are not automatically continuous. The following is a necessary and sufficient condition on a (semi)norm to make the group operations continuous. We leave the verification to the reader.
\begin{fact}
Let $\lambda$ be a (semi)norm on a group $G$. Then $G$ with the inherited topology is a topological group if and only if for every $x\in G$ and every $\epsilon>0$ there exists $\delta>0$ such that $\forall y\in G (\lambda(y)<\delta\Rightarrow \lambda(x^{-1}\cdot y\cdot x)<\varepsilon)$; in other words, the function $y\to \lambda(x^{-1}\cdot y\cdot x)$ is continuous at $1_G$.
\end{fact}
We shall call such (semi)norms \emph{continuous (semi)norms}. Note that when a (semi)norm is conjugacy-invariant then it is continuous.

Let now $G$ be a group equipped with a continuous (semi)norm $\lambda$. It follows that to each $x\in G$ we can associate some modulus of continuity $\Gamma_x^G:{\mathbb{R}}_0^+\rightarrow {\mathbb{R}}^+_0$ of the function $g\to \lambda(x^{-1}\cdot g\cdot x)$ at $1_G$, i.e. the function with the property that $\lambda(x^{-1}\cdot g\cdot x)\leq\Gamma_x^G(\lambda(g))$ for every $g\in G$. We shall call such a function a modulus of continuity for $g\in G$, or just shortly MOC.

In general, moduli of continuity can be any functions that are continuous at $0$ and equal to $0$ there. However, in the case of functions `$g\to \lambda(x^{-1}\cdot g\cdot x)$' we moreover have that the corresponding modulus of continuity $\Gamma_x$ satisfies
\begin{itemize}
\item $\Gamma_x(r)\geq r$ for every $r\geq 0$,
\item $\Gamma_x$ is dominated by an affine function,\; indeed for every $r\geq 0$ we have $\Gamma_x(r)\leq 2\lambda(x)+r$.
\end{itemize}
We note that in \cite{DiGa}, in this context of groups with norms (resp. left-invariant metrics), these moduli are called scales. \\

We shall conclude this section with several other facts concerning normed groups.

First, we shall recall the classical result of Birkhoff and Kakutani connecting first-countable topological groups with (semi)normed groups.
\begin{thm}[Birkhoff-Kakutani]
Let $G$ be a first-countable topological group. Then there exists a continuous seminorm on $G$ which induces the topology of $G$.

If $G$ is Hausdorff, then the seminorm is a norm.
\end{thm}

Next we want to recall the following notion from geometric group theory that will be useful later.
\begin{defin}
Let $(G,\lambda)$ be a normed topological group. We say that $\lambda$ is \emph{proper} if for every $r>0$ the set $\{g\in G:\lambda(g)\leq r\}$ is compact.

In case $(G,\lambda)$ is countable discrete, it means that for every $r>0$ the set $\{g\in G:\lambda(g)\leq r\}$ is finite.
\end{defin}

If we have a group with a continuous seminorm we can always quotient to get a genuine norm on the quotient group.
\begin{fact}\label{makequotient}
Let $G$ be a group with a (continuous) seminorm $\lambda$. Then the set $N=\{g\in G:\lambda(g)=0\}$ is a closed normal subgroup, and $\lambda$ is constant on any left coset of $N$, thus it determines a (continuous) norm on $G/N$.
\end{fact}
\begin{proof}
$N$ is by the definition of the topology on $G$ closed. Since for any $g,h\in G$ we have $\lambda(g)=\lambda(g^{-1})$, $\lambda(g\cdot h)\leq \lambda(g)+\lambda(h)$ and $\lambda$ is continuous, it immediately follows that $N$ is a normal subgroup. Take any $x\in G$ and $g\in N$. We show that $\lambda(x)=\lambda(x\cdot g)$. We have $\lambda(x\cdot g)\leq \lambda(x)+\lambda(g)=\lambda(x)=\lambda(x\cdot g\cdot g^{-1})\leq \lambda(x\cdot g)+\lambda(g^{-1})=\lambda(x\cdot g)$.
\end{proof}
Now for a moment, we switch to continuous left-invariant\\ (pseudo)metrics rather than (semi)norms, where by a \emph{continuous} left-invariant (pseudo)metric we mean a left-invariant (pseudo)metric whose associated (semi)norm is continuous. So assume we are given a group $G$ with a continuous left-invariant (pseudo)metric $d$. It is well known that a metric completion of $G$ with respect to $d$ need not to be a group; respectively, it is always a semigroup, however the inverse operation might not extend to such a completion. Consider for example $S_\infty$, the infinite permutation group of ${\mathbb{N}}$, with left-invariant $d$ defined as $d(x,y)=\max\{1/n:x(n)\neq y(n)\}$. Completion of $S_\infty$ with respect to this metric is the semigroup of all injective mappings from ${\mathbb{N}}$ into ${\mathbb{N}}$.

\begin{observation}\label{obs2}
However, one can always consider the completion of $G$ with respect to the metric $D(x,y):=d(x,y)+d(x^{-1},y^{-1})$. This completion is always a group. We shall call it a \emph{group metric completion} of $G$. Note that it is nothing but adding limits for all Cauchy sequences $(x_n)_n\subseteq G$ such that the sequence of inverses $(x^{-1}_n)_n$ is also Cauchy. The metric $d$ thus extends to the group metric completion.\\
\end{observation}

Finally, since we shall work with free groups often we recall some basic facts and fix some notation related to them here. Let $A$ be a non-empty set. Recall that the free group $F_A$ generated by $A$ is the free group having elements of $A$ as free generators. Consider the disjoint union $\{1\}\coprod A\coprod A^{-1}$ denoted by $\bar{A}$, where $A^{-1}$ is the set of formal inverses of $A$, i.e. $A^{-1}=\{a^{-1}:a\in A\}$. One can view the free group $F_A$ as the set of all reduced words over the alphabet $\bar{A}$. A word $w=w_1\ldots w_n$, where $w_1,\ldots,w_n\in\bar{A}$ is reduced if either $n=1$ and $w_1=1$, or there is no $i\leq n$ such that $w_i=1$ and $w_i=w_{i+1}^{-1}$. For any word (not necessarily reduced) $w$ over the alphabet $\bar{A}$, by $w'$ we denote the reduction of $w$, i.e. the unique reduced word obtained from $w$ by successively removing the pairs $w_i, w_{i+1}$, where $w_i=w_{i+1}^{-1}$, and letters $1$ from $w$ till it is reduced. In case this procedure leads to an empty word, we 
set $w'$ to be $1$. For any word $w$, by $|w|$ we denote the length of the word, i.e. the number of letters from alphabet used to make $w$.

Then the group multiplication of two reduced words $w_1$ and $w_2$ is defined to be $(w_1w_2)'$, i.e. concatenation of two words followed by reduction. The inverse of a reduced word $w_1\ldots w_n$ is the reduced word $w_n^{-1}\ldots w_1^{-1}$. The unit is the reduced word $1$.\\

We shall also use the following basic observation.
\begin{observation}\label{obs1}
Let $H$ be an at most countable group equipped with a (continuous) norm $\lambda$. Then there exists a (continuous) seminorm $\lambda'$ on $F_\infty$, the free group of countably many free generators, such that the quotient $F_\infty/N$, where $N=\{h\in F_\infty:\lambda'(h)=0\}$, is isometrically isomorphic to $(H,\lambda)$.
\end{observation}
Indeed, just pick some countable set of generators (with possible repetition) $(h_n)_n$. For each reduced word $w$ over the alphabet $\{1,h_n,h_n^{-1}:n\in{\mathbb{N}}\}$ denote by $w_H$ its evaluation in $H$, i.e. the group element of $H$ that corresponds to the natural evaluating of $w$ in $H$. Then we consider the free group freely generated by $(h_n)_n$ and define the seminorm $\lambda'$ by the formula $\lambda'(w)=\lambda(w_H)$ for any word $w$ over the alphabet $\{1,h_n,h_n^{-1}:n\in{\mathbb{N}}\}$.\\

\subsection{Normed ultraproducts of normed groups and group embeddings into them}
Metric ultraproducts of groups with bi-invariant metric, resp. conjugacy-invariant norms are well-known from the literature. Let $\mathcal{M}$ be some class of groups equipped with bi-invariant metric/conjugacy-invariant norms. It is of great current interest which (discrete) groups can be embedded into a metric ultraproduct of groups from $\mathcal{M}$.

The most interesting cases are when $\mathcal{M}$ is the set of unitary groups of finite rank equipped with the Hilbert-Schmidt distance and when $\mathcal{M}$ is the set of finite permutation groups equipped with the normalized Hamming distance. For the former, such groups, that can be embedded into a metric ultraproduct of groups from $\mathcal{M}$, are then called hyperlinear and were introduced by R\v adulescu (\cite{Rad}). They are related to the Connes' embedding problem for groups from operator algebras (see \cite{Con}). For the latter, such groups are called sofic and were introduced by Gromov (\cite{Gro}). They are related to the Gottschalk's surjunctivity conjecture. The major open problem is whether every group is hyperlinear and sofic (we note that every sofic group is hyperlinear \cite{ElSz}). We refer the reader to the survey \cite{Pe-sh} where these classes of groups are defined and metric ultraproducts of groups with bi-invariant metrics are treated.

When $\mathcal{M}$ is the set of all finite groups equipped with some bi-invariant metric, then such $\mathcal{M}$-approximable groups are called weakly sofic. Weakly sofic groups as a generalization of sofic groups were introduced by Glebsky and Rivera in \cite{GlRi} (see also \cite{Gl}) as the existence of a non-weakly sofic group is equivalent to a certain conjecture about pro-finite topology on finitely generated free groups.

Let us also mention that when $\mathcal{M}$ is the set of general linear groups of finite rank with the normalized rank distance, then such\\ $\mathcal{M}$-approximable groups are called linear sofic and were introduced by Arzhantseva and Paunescu in \cite{ArPa}. Finally, let us mention that when $\mathcal{M}$ is the set of finite groups with a commutator-contractive bi-invariant metric, then such $\mathcal{M}$-approximable groups were called as $F_c$-approximable groups in \cite{Thom}.

So far, it has been open whether there is a group which is \emph{not} approximable by any such classes $\mathcal{M}$ mentioned with the exception when $\mathcal{M}$ is $F_c$ as it was proved by Thom in \cite{Thom} that the Higman's group is not $F_c$-approximable.\\


Let now $(G_n,\lambda_n)_{n\in{\mathbb{N}}}$ be a sequence of general normed groups. We would like to define a metric/normed ultraproduct of them.  We recall some definitions here. Fix some non-principal ultrafilter $\mathcal{U}$ on ${\mathbb{N}}$. At first, one takes the direct product $\prod_n G_n$. In order to define an ultraproduct norm there one has to restrict to a subgroup of the product of those elements whose coordinates have norm bounded by one common constant. That is, let $\mathbb{P}=\{(g_n)_n:\forall n\, (g_n\in G_n),\, \exists K\forall n (\lambda_n(g_n)\leq K)\}$. Then for each $(g_n)_n$ one set $\lambda((g_n))=\lim_{\mathcal{U}} \lambda_n(g_n)$. In this way, one gets a seminorm on $P$. In order to get a norm, one needs to take a quotient of $(P,\lambda)$ by $N=\{(g_n)_n\in P:\lambda((g_n))=0\}$. Unless $\lambda$ is continuous, $N$ will not be a normal subgroup though. If all $\lambda_n$'s are conjugacy invariant then $\lambda$ will be conjugacy-invariant as well, and thus continuous. So $N$ is a normal 
subgroup.

If not all $\lambda_n$'s are conjugacy-invariant then the construction above gives an ultraproduct seminorm which however does not have to be continuous, thus the subgroup of zero-seminorm elements will not have to be normal. In such a case, one has to restrict the subgroup $P$ more. We call an element $(g_n)_n\in P$ continuous in the ultraproduct if for every $\varepsilon>0$ there exist $\delta>0$ and $A\in\mathcal{U}$ such that for every $n\in A$ and every $h_n\in G_n$ such that $\lambda_n(h_n)\leq \delta$ we have $\lambda_n(g_n^{-1}\cdot h_n\cdot g_n)<\varepsilon$ and $\lambda_N(g_n\cdot h_n\cdot g_n^{-1})<\varepsilon$. Let $P'\leq P$ be the subset of elements continuous in the ultraproduct. It is straightforward to check that it is a subgroup. Note that if $\lambda_n$'s were conjugacy-invariant, then $P'=P$. We consider the ultraproduct seminorm $\lambda$ on $P'$. We now claim that the seminorm is continuous, thus the subgroup of zero-seminorm elements is normal and we can quotient. Let $(h_n)_n\in P'$ 
be such that $\lambda((h_n))=0$. We shall check that $\lambda((g_n)^{-1}\cdot(h_n)\cdot (g_n))=0$. It suffices to check that for any $\varepsilon$ there is $A_\varepsilon\in\mathcal{U}$ such that for every $n\in A_\varepsilon$ we have $\lambda_n(g_n^{-1}\cdot h_n\cdot g_n)<\varepsilon$. Since $(g_n)_n$ is continuous in the ultraproduct, by definition there is some $B\in\mathcal{U}$ and $\delta>0$ such that for every $n\in B$ we have $\lambda_n(g_n^{-1}\cdot h_n\cdot g_n)<\varepsilon$ provided $\lambda_n(h_n)<\delta$. However, since $\lambda((h_n))=0$ there is some $C\in\mathcal{U}$ such that for every $n\in C$ we have $\lambda_n(h_n)<\delta$. Thus it suffices to take $A_\varepsilon=B\cap C$.\\

We note that one type of example of $(g_n)_n\in P$ that is an element of $P'$ is such that there is a MOC $\Gamma$ such that $\Gamma$ is a MOC for $g_n$ in $(G_n,\lambda_n)$ for every $n$.\\

Finally, we make some observations regarding completeness. It is known that ultraproducts of normed vector spaces or groups with conjugacy-invariant norms are complete. A group with a norm cannot be always complete as noted in Observation \ref{obs2}. However, they might be group metrically completed as observed there. We claim that metric ultraproducts of normed groups are always group metrically complete.

